The National Trust is listening to bats' secret life
A new study of property in the Scottish mountainous regions is being conducted to discover how bats use the area in their search for food.
There is hope that the discoveries will provide answers to the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future protection activities.
A study of the National Trust for Scotland will monitor ordinary and soprano bats, as well as brown bats with long ears and daubenton bats in Inverrow Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activities during the season.
The En-Atch-Es staff and volunteers will also carry mobile research using manual detectors.
Expert analysis of sounds from all videos will determine the frequency depending on the type of bats.
A map of habitats will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the area.
Rob Devar, an advisor to nature protection at the EN-TI-ES, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of living are most important for bats and how each species is used.
This information will help determine the benefits of managing habitats, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain bat forests and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain has decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect beds and the loss of dwellings.
Windwinds and lights also pose a risk, as well as sticky molds and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as attacks on domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
Yet, because of their night - hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location technique to find insects and obstacles in the flight path.
En-Ti-Es, who cares for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, bed inspections, and sometimes rescues.
The organization even founded the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Triv estate in Damfris and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species living in Scotland.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Triv we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, very old two and very good dwellings.
But there are many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and other properties will help us learn more about what they need to make progress."
He stresses that it is important to check whether there are bats before real estate renovations are done because the unconscious destruction of beds can destroy up to 400 females and cubs, and destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture, or harass their beds.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official in the bat protection Trust, encourages the public to help.
She said: “We still need to learn a lot about bats and other species of ours, we just don’t know how they live. ”
