New information on the red tide: concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatas, and Sarasota
The latest report by the Committee on Fish and Wildlifes in Florida shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions for irregular algas bloom have been observed in the area of the counties of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which suggests a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide, the result of the blooming red algae, stretches about 130 miles on the coast of northern Pinellas County to South Li County.
Parts of the red tide can be seen about 10 miles on the shores of Hillsboro County, but still the number is smaller than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
During last week, the following concentrations were observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of the Pinellas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of the Hillsboro County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Sarasota County, common to middle concentrations in Charlotte County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Li County, as well as low concentrations in Collier County.
In the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Li, and Collier, cases of respiratory irritation continue.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida during last week.
